In computing, return oriented programming or (ROP) is a technique for achieving arbitrary code execution, to subvert the control flow of a program.
In ROP, the target program is opened to gaps in code in order to execute arbitrary code, while trying not to violate sequential execution. Gaps are where code next to itself will return its result, viewing the machine code as a function call graph. ROP also stores open instructions (which facilitate the insertion of directed objects, while preserving the machine code) in a buffer. Finally, the buffer is overridden with instructions that are uniquely accessed only by the attacker. This allows for the restriction of the program being modified, and guarantees that code such as system calls are not executed.

There are many types of stars that can explode in this way. The most common example being a red giant star, but there are also stars in which two massive stars may collide to create a special type of supernova called a neutron star. A star that is so large that it lacks the central composition it needs to survive implodes on itself creating a black hole. These grow to be incredibly dense, and in some cases, are as small as the mass of a family-sized minivan weighing about as much as 5 pillows.

OpenBSD "pledge feature?"
The OpenBSD Project started in 1995, where engineers and developers worked together to produce yet another operating system that meets the demands of developers, system administrators, and cryptographers everywhere. At the moment they are fairly well known for introducing the OpenSSH networking suite and many people are feeling grateful that it is used in many other operating systems today.
One other cool feature which has been added to OpenBSD is the “pledge(8)” feature. What it does is, it controls what programs are allowed to do with namespaces like the UNIX socket family, to device nodes, to directories, and other filesystem locations. Essentially, pledge(8) toggles what sockets, files, or directories is available to execute. This should drastically mitigate the possibilities of a well done man-in-the-middle attack. It makes it where a process can only open certain resources, if they are permitted to by pledge(8).
If, for example, you unpledge the contents of your /etc/passwd, this still does not allow any process that is not already being run and it will not grant any permission, although the process could still save itself. If a new program is inserted on the system’s binary tree the file won’t be unlisted from the filesystem tree or maps as it is by default.
